{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641977"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:34:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:34:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17922"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17922"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.93,0,0.07,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10636"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76896"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10636"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17922"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62401"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5099"},{"type":"tags","id":"10538"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24777"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24780"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76896","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76896"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of nausea, vomiting, and abdominal pain. She has a known history of type 1 diabetes mellitus, diagnosed two years ago, and is on insulin therapy. She has been feeling unwell and has not been able to take her insulin regularly. On examination, she appears dehydrated. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Laboratory investigations reveal a blood glucose level of 22 mmol/L (3.9-5.5), ketone bodies present in urine, and arterial blood gas showing a pH of 7.25 (7.35-7.45).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would we expect for the metabolic profile of a patient with type 1 diabetes in this scenario?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["High concentration of ketone bodies","Increased pH of blood","Low beta-oxidation in the liver","Decreased lipolysis","Normal blood glucose levels"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient with type 1 diabetes presents with symptoms suggestive of diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA), a common acute complication due to insulin deficiency. In DKA, there is a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh concentration of ketone bodies\u003C/strong\u003E due to increased lipolysis and beta-oxidation of fatty acids in the liver, as the body attempts to use fat as an alternative energy source in the absence of insulin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased pH of blood\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as DKA is characterised by metabolic acidosis, leading to a decreased blood pH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow beta-oxidation in the liver\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as beta-oxidation is actually increased in the absence of insulin, contributing to the production of ketone bodies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased lipolysis\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as lipolysis is increases in the absence of insulin, leading to the release of free fatty acids that are converted to ketone bodies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal blood glucose levels\u003C/strong\u003E are incorrect, as the patient has hyperglycaemia, evidenced by the elevated blood glucose level of 22 mmol/L, due to the lack of insulin to facilitate glucose uptake into cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Type 1 diabetes is characterised by an absolute deficiency of insulin due to autoimmune destruction of pancreatic beta cells.","In the absence of insulin, there is increased lipolysis and beta-oxidation of fatty acids, leading to the production of ketone bodies.","Diabetic ketoacidosis is a common complication of type 1 diabetes, resulting in metabolic acidosis with decreased blood pH."],"references":["DiMeglio LA, Evans-Molina C, Oram RA. Type 1 diabetes. Lancet. 2018 Jun 16;391(10138):2449-2462. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(18)31320-5. PMID: 29916386; PMCID: PMC6661119","Lucier J, Mathias PM. Type 1 Diabetes. 2024 Oct 5. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29939535","Giwa AM, Ahmed R, Omidian Z, Majety N, Karakus KE, Omer SM, Donner T, Hamad ARA. Current understandings of the pathogenesis of type 1 diabetes: Genetics to environment. World J Diabetes. 2020 Jan 15;11(1):13-25. doi: 10.4239/wjd.v11.i1.13. PMID: 31938470; PMCID: PMC6927819"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62401"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17922"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62401"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T18:33:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T18:33:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10636"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76896"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":